#week-title("Two", "First Mineral Dissolution")

=== Core Teaching

The first mineral dissolution is the operative beginning of Year Three's
laboratory work in earnest. Having chosen the mineral substrate in Week 1,
the student now prepares the acid medium and conducts the first dissolution.

*The acid medium.* For the Via Humida, the dissolving medium must be suited
to the mineral being worked. In the tradition's accessible entry to this work,
vegetable-derived acids serve as the first solvents:

- *Strong wine vinegar (acetic acid):* The natural choice as a bridge from
  the Year Two Sulphur work. It will dissolve copper and iron moderately
  well, and will extract a fraction from stibnite. Concentration: use the
  strongest available, or concentrate by gentle evaporation before use.
- *Fermented plant vinegar of higher acidity:* If available from the student's
  own preparations, this is preferable to commercial vinegar as it carries
  additional vegetable virtue.

For those working with iron: the dissolution of iron in concentrated wine
vinegar produces a complex mixture of iron acetate compounds and sometimes a
green to brown precipitate — this is the beginning of the "vitriol" fraction
and is of great alchemical interest.

For those working with copper: dissolution in warm wine vinegar produces a
characteristic blue-green solution (copper acetate) of great beauty and clear
Venusian quality.

For those working with stibnite: the dissolution is partial and yields the
sour antimony fraction already encountered in Month 1, now more concentrated.

#lab[
  *First Mineral Dissolution Protocol*
  + *Prepare the acid medium:* Warm strong wine vinegar to 40–60°C in a water
    bath. Do not boil.
  + *Add mineral substrate:* Small quantity — 2–5g of the chosen mineral, either
    as filings, powder (iron), thin sheet (copper), or coarse stibnite powder.
  + *Cover loosely* and maintain warmth for 2–4 hours. Observe and record
    colour changes in the solution at each hour.
  + *Do not seal completely* — the dissolution generates some gas (CO₂ from
    acid-carbonate reactions if tartar contamination is present; H₂ from iron
    dissolution). Allow gas to escape.
  + *After dissolution period:* Filter the solution through paper. The filtrate
    is the first dissolved mineral fraction. The undissolved residue is retained.
  + *Record precisely:* colour of filtrate, presence of any precipitate, smell
    (with caution), approximate volume recovered.
]

=== Topics This Week

- Choosing and preparing the acid medium
- The first dissolution: protocol and observation
- Reading the colour change as a diagnostic of what is occurring
- The undissolved residue: what remains fixed and what it will yield

#inner-work[
  *The Dissolution as Inner Correlate*

  Every dissolution in the outer laboratory corresponds to a dissolution in
  the inner work. Westcott's Human level of the triple point is active here:
  what aspect of your established identity, habit, or self-concept is being
  dissolved by the demands of Year Three?

  Do not force an answer. Observe honestly. Sometimes the dissolution is
  imperceptible from within; it becomes visible only in retrospect. Record
  whatever is genuinely present, even if it is "nothing obvious yet."
]

